In perusing Stern&#039;s book, I stumbled across the following gem (the likes of which this book is no doubt full). In discussing the brevity of the Biur ha-gra, Stern refers to one comment of the Gaon: 
&quot;For example, when Karo interprets the biblical injunction against sacrificing an animal with its child as referring to specific animals, Elijah comments: &#039;See there [Chullin] 79b and in the Midrashic work Torat Kohanim [Emor, section 8, chapter 7]. But Rabbi Isaac Alfasi [Chullin 27b] and Rabbi Asher ben Yechiel [Chullin chapter 4, topic 3] say it also refers to a bull and not a non-domesticated animal, a sheep nor chickens.&quot; 
Reading this, I was puzzled: how could Rabbi Isaac Alfasi say that the injunction does not apply to sheep, does it not say explicitly ושור או שה אותו ואת בנו לא תשחטו ביום אחד? 
Looking up the original comment of the Gaon, I found the following: The Shulhan Arukh (Yoreh Deah 16:7) says אין איסור אותו ואת בנו אלא בבהמה טהורה בלבד, שנאמר: ושור או שה אותו ואת בנו לא תשחטו ביום אחד. On this, the Gaon comments: אין איסור כו&#039;. שם ע&quot;ט ב&#039; ובת&quot;כ והביאו הרי&quot;ף והרא&quot;ש שור ולא חיה שה ולא עופות. (To translate: &quot;Ibid. 79b and in Torat Kohanim, cited by R. Alfasi and R. Asher, &#039;An ox and non a non-domesticated animal, a sheep and not birds&#039;.&quot;) Stern&#039;s interpretation, which is infinitely more creative, sees here not a reference, but a dispute about the parameters of the mitzvah, with the majority of the opinions on which the Shulhan arukh is based siding against a pasuk. I think this is the only example Stern gives of a halakhic comment of the Gaon. Anyone can write a book on the Gaon, but only Stern could have written &quot;The Genius.&quot;
